We have a deeper understanding to the effects of the transmission coefficient β on the basis of these useful research about deterministic epidemic models. However, in the real world, the spread of infectious diseases are always subject to random fluctuations, it is more reasonable and practical to study the influence of random factors. Usually, environmental noise can be simply divided into white noise and colored noise. The disease transmission coefficient β in the SIR model is a key parameter for disease transmission, so it is interesting to assess the effect of the perturbation parameter β on the model. In applications we usually estimate it by an average value plus errors. Assume these errors follow a normal distribution, that is,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
