In the study of SIR deterministic model, disease eradication and stability are two of the most concerns. But for stochastic model, the equilibrium does not exist. Therefore, we can not show the persistence of the infection by proving the stability of the equilibrium. In this section, we will investigate the dynamics of the stochastic epidemic model (1.4). First, we will prove that system (1.4) has a stationary distribution, which implies the disease is recurrent. We will give the conclusion that if \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${ {\mathcal R} }_{0}^{S} > 1$$\end{document}ℛ0S>1, the densities of the distributions of the solutions to system (1.4) can converge in L1 to an invariant density.

